dsiter.row

Interface IRowAccessor

  • All Known Subinterfaces:
    IColumnAccessor, IColumnAccessor.BOOLEAN, IColumnAccessor.DOUBLE, IColumnAccessor.FLOAT, IColumnAccessor.INT, IColumnAccessor.LONG, IColumnAccessor.STRING, IRowAccessor.BOOLEAN, IRowAccessor.DOUBLE, IRowAccessor.FLOAT, IRowAccessor.INT, IRowAccessor.LONG, IRowAccessor.STRING
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AndOperator, CaretOperator, DivideOperator, EqualsOperator, GreaterThanEqualsOperator, GreaterThanOperator, LessThanEqualsOperator, LessThanOperator, MinusOperator, ModuloOperator, NotOperator, NthRootOperator, OrOperator, PlusOperator, SqrtOperator, TimesOperator, TypedBinaryOperator, TypedUnaryOperator

    public interface IRowAccessor
    An interface representing objects that return values from Rows. The returned values may be simple column reads (see: IColumnAccessor), computed values (see: everything in dsiter.operator), or static values that have nothing at all to do with the passed Row (see: ConstantAccessor).

    A plain IRowAccessor will return its value as an Object, but there are also type-specific inner interfaces, like IRowAccessor.INT, that can return the same value as a strongly-typed int. Plain IRowAccessors can be converted to their typed counterparts via methods like asIntAccessor(). The default implementations of these methods perform a simple cast operation on this, but some implementations override this with more sophisticated behavior. For example some implementations override these methods to return an inner accessor of the correct type (see: TypedBinaryOperator, TypedUnaryOperator).

    All as[Type]Accessor() methods will throw an Exception (usually a ClassCastException) if the accessor is not actually of that type. In general though, if getType() returns ColumnType.INT, then asIntAccessor() should not throw.

      • asIntAccessor

        default IRowAccessor.INT asIntAccessor()
        Convert this IRowAccessor to an IRowAccessor.INT. The default implementation of this method simply casts this to IRowAccessor.INT, but some subclasses may wish to provide more sophisticated implementations, e.g. by casting and returning an inner accessor to the approriate type.

        Note: this method will throw if getType() does not return ColumnType.INT.

        Returns:
        An IRowAccessor.INT representation of this instance
